        <title><m>\S IV.8</m>: Arithmetic Sums</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="1in">
                    <title>Motivation: Arithmetic Sums  </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Arithmetic series aren't useful, but partial sums are. How can we utilize their structure
                            to compute them efficiently?
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Definition: Arithmetic Sequence</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            An <term>arithmetic sequence</term> is a sequence of the form
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                a, a + d, a+2d, a+3d, \dots
                            </me>.
                        The rule for a generic term is <m>a_n = a + nd</m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Example 1: Sums of Arithmetic Sequences</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Consider the sequence
                            <me>
                                0,1,2,3,4,\dots, k
                            </me>
                            which has the corresponding sum <m>\sum_{n=0}^k n </m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can use the structure of this sequence to compute that 
                            <me>
                                \sum_{n=0}^k n = \frac{k(k+1)}{2}
                            </me>.
                            See our class notes or your textbook for details.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Example 2: Sums of Arithmetic Sequences</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Consider the sum <m>\sum_{n=0}^{100} (2 + 3n) </m>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We can use the structure of this sequence to compute that 
                            <me>
                                \sum_{n=0}^{100} (2 + 3n) =2 \dot (101) + \frac{3(100)(101)}{2}
                            </me>.
                            See our class notes or your textbook for details.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Practice: Sums of Arithmetic Sequences</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Compute the following sums:
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sum_{n=0}^{50} (4 + 7n) </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sum_{n=1}^{70} (-6 + 2n) </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sum_{n=10}^{60} (2 - 3n) </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            As a challenge, compute a formula for the generic sum
                            <me>
                                \sum_{n=0}^k ( a+ dn)
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                       <m>\sum_{n=0}^{50} (4 + 7n) = 4\cdot (51) + \frac{7(50)(51)}{2} </m> 
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sum_{n=1}^{70} (-6 + 2n) = -6 \cdot (70) + \frac{2(70)(71)}{2} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>\sum_{n=10}^{60} (2 - 3n) = 2 \cdot (51) -3 \cdot \frac{70(51)}{2} </m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                            See our class notes for details.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

